<section xml:id="section-outomces">
  <title>Course Learning Outcomes</title>
  <p>
    This course is organized into learning outcomes, and each
    section of the notes (and each video) reflection one of the
    learning outcomes. There are three
    types of these: core learning outcomes (CLOs), stretch learning
    outcomes (SLOs) and holistic learning outcomes (HLOs). The main
    content of the course is organized by the CLOs and the SLOs: you
    will see each section of the course labelled by one of these.
    The HLOs are major ideas, themes and skills that run throughout
    the course but are not isolated to any one area. I'll try to
    point out the development of the HLOs over the whole course. 
  </p>
  <p>
    Here are the learning outcomes for the course. These are all
    stated with active verbs: a learning outcome is something that a
    student will be able to do, which can be demonstrated and
    assessed. You can preface all of these with <sq>A student
    completing this course should be able to <m>\ldots</m></sq>.
  </p>
  <p>
    Here are the 20 core learning outcomes.  
  </p>
  <ol>
    <li>
      Describe and manipulate equations of line in Cartesian
      coordinates. 
    </li>
    <li>
      Describe and manipulate equations of conics in Cartesian
      coordinates. 
    </li>
    <li>
      Solve intersection problems with simple loci (lines, conics,
      etc) in Cartesian coordinates.
    </li>
    <li>
      Manipulate functions with pointwise operations, composition
      and inversion. 
    </li>
    <li>
      Use functions as mathematical models for real world
      situations, including interpretation of coefficients.
    </li>
    <li>
      Use differential equations to describe growth in models,
      including the Mathusian model and the logistic growth models. 
    </li>
    <li>
      Use phase lines to qualitatively describe the behaviour of
      solutions to autonomous differential equations. 
    </li>
    <li>
      Calculate limits of functions approaching finite values.
    </li>
    <li>
      Determine continuity of piecewise functions and articular the
      connection between limits and continuity. 
    </li>
    <li>
      Use asymptotic analysis to calculate limits of functions
      approaching infinity and long term behaviour of models. 
    </li>
    <li>
      Describe the derivative as an approximation process calculated
      by a limit. 
    </li>
    <li>
      Use derivative rules for pointwise operations (linearity,
      power rule, product rule, quotient rule). 
    </li>
    <li>
      Use the chain rule for derivative of compositions. 
    </li>
    <li>
      Use L'Hôpital's rule to calculate limits.
    </li>
    <li>
      Describe the Riemann integral as an approximation process
      calculated by a limit. 
    </li>
    <li>
      Use the fundamental theory of calculus, basic
      antiderivatives, linearity and the power rule  to solve
      integrals. 
    </li>
    <li>
      Apply the substitution rule to solve integrals. 
    </li>
    <li>
      Use derivative to find extrema, find intervals of increase and
      decrease, and solve optimzation problems. 
    </li>
    <li>
      Use the tools of the course to sketch functions without the
      aid of a computer graphing tool. 
    </li>
    <li>
      Use the tools and concepts of the course to analyse and
      critique functions as models of real-world situations. 
    </li>
  </ol>
  <p>
    Here are the 5 stretch learning outcomes.  
  </p>
  <ol>
    <li>
      Calculate derivatives using the limit definition of the
      derivative instead of the usual derivative rules. 
    </li>
    <li>
      Recount and explain proofs of the derivative rules (power
      rule, product rule, chain rule, inverse derivative,
      derivatives of exponential functions.) 
    </li>
    <li>
      Prove the identities for inverse derivatives of trigonometric
      functions. 
    </li>
    <li>
      Use L'Hôpital's rule as a way to prove comparisons of
      asymptotic order. 
    </li>
    <li>
      Solve separable differential equations with antiderivatice
      covered so far in the course, including initial values. 
    </li>
    <li>
      Use the Riemann definition of the integral and common identity
      for finite sums to calculate integrals of polynomial
      functions. 
    </li>
  </ol>
  <p>
    Here are the 5 holistic learning outcomes.
  </p>
  <ol>
    <li>
      Describe the limitations of algebra to solve certain dynamic
      system and the way that calculus provide new tools and
      techniques to approach these previously unsolvable problems. 
    </li>
    <li>
      Describe the conection between algebra and geometry using
      catersian coordinates, specifically concerning equations of
      lines, intersection problems, slopes and derivatives, graphs
      of functions. 
    </li>
    <li>
      Describe the limitations of algebraic techniques, the role of
      approximation processes, and the importance of limits in the
      creation of calculus. 
    </li>
    <li>
      Holistically use the techniques of calculus to analyse
      functions, including domain, range, increase and decrease,
      concavity, extrema, continuity, limits and asymptopes. 
    </li>
    <li>
      Holistically use the techniques of calculus to analyse and
      critique models including questions of realism and viability. 
    </li>
    <li>
      Use clear and precise written and oral communication to
      describe the mathematical concepts, calculations and processes
      involved in the core and stretch learning outcomes. 
    </li>
  </ol>
</section>
